Approximately 15 gallons of UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide released from an above ground storage tank due to an overfill. The CTMV was offloading product pneumatically with a tractor compressor. When the tank was nearly full, the internal valve failed to close and product continued to flow, resulting in the overflow and release of product. The release impacted the concrete containment area within the facility and an area of soil covered with stone. A contractor responded to perform cleanup activities. The free liquid in the containment area was pumped into a drum. The impacted soil area was hand excavated and containerized into drums. All waste was transported off site for disposal. No neutralizing agents were used per request of the facility. The cleanup was supervised by an LSP.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the Clean Harbors Clackamas, OR facility for an offload in order to transfer and consolidate its waste onto a van trailer to its intended waste disposal facility. While off-loading facility personnel noticed that a leaking super sack container. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking super sack; the super sack was repacked into drums for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The facility floor was cleaned and returned to service. The release was reported to the Oregon Emergency Response System operator: Misty, report # 2016-0816.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or was observed. The release was the direct result of improper container selection and preparation. The driver has been retrained on proper container inspection, selection and preparation for solid vs liquid waste streams. The driver has been instructed that solid rated containers with excessive liquid must be rejected for transportation or repackaged into appropriately rated containers. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container shipments of waste containing excess liquid. The shipper has also been instructed to re-evaluate the profile and re-characterize as a liquid waste stream.

column168: During unloading activities, one 330 gallon poly tote containing UN1814 "Renoclean 7176" was discovered with a loose cap releasing approximately 12 liquid ounces of material to the top of the tote. During unloading activities, one metal cylinder containing UN1077 Propylene was discovered to be leaking from a damaged valve. A contractor responded and cautioned off the area. Due to the high LEL and VOC levels, the contractor allowed the cylinder to continue leaking before entry was made into the trailer. Once the cylinder finished leaking the contractor secured the cylinder with wood boards to help prevent another release. The shipper was contacted who reported that they will send a team out to access the cylinder.

column168: Our driver was heading north on I75 towards Nashville TN, when the excess on one of his portable ratchet straps got loose.  The strap got tangled in the wheel causing the strap to tighten and crush 5 pales of the cold adhesive.  The driver then exited off of the interstate to get some breakfast.  The driver was in the McDonald's drive thru when he noticed the leakage and immediately pulled off to the side into the parking lot.  Our fleet manager was able to get to him with absorbent to clean up the mess.  The absorbent did an excellent job of drying up the spill.  All told, about 2-3 gallons was spilled onto the parking lot, and it took them about an hour to clean it up.  Our fleet manager instructed McDonald's management not to let anyone drive over it until about an hour later when it had sufficient time to dry.
column169: Our fleet manager has already held a class on a more efficient and safe way to keep excess from a portable ratchet strap getting loose.  This involves folding the excess and crimping it between the strap and the trailer, thereby locking it in.

The two loads were juxtaposed when offered, so the hazmat load was not flagged properly in our dispatch system.  A new driver picked up the load, which was incorrectly flagged as a non-hazmat load and failed to follow SOP; driver did not call in for a hazmat briefing and he also did not affix placards to the container. The load was then offered as an inter modal load to our rail partner without required EDI hazmat billing, hence it moved undeclared.  When the load out-gated from the railroad, our driver on the final delivery noticed the mistake and brought it our attention.
column169: Customer needs to communicate better when loads will contain hazmat; this will be discussed with them in detail.  Our driver has also been coached - our SOP is for a driver to review his/her bills and to call in for a briefing, which was not followed here.  Safety messages are being sent to our vehicles reminding drivers of SOP.

At approximately 12:00 pm on Tuesday, April 12, 2016, two employees were loading a rail car with supplemental fuel.  The operator on top of the rail car opened the manway lid to check the pumping operation and rail car volume.  He called to the operator on the ground to inform him the rail car was reaching capacity and to stop the movement of material.  The operator on the ground was wearing earplugs, thus he did not immediately hear the operator on top of the rail car.  As a result, the rail car was over-filled.  After shutting down the pump and closing the valves, the operators immediately notified the plant manager.  A total of 5 gallons of material ran down the side of the rail car.  Approximately four gallons of material was captured by the spill diversion devices and about one gallon landed on the gravel near the rail car.  The excess material in the rail car was pumped back into the supplemental fuel tank system to allow for outage or room for expansion in the rail car during transportation.  The material in containment devices was also returned to the tank system.  No injuries occurred as a result of the incident.  Heritage personnel acted promptly in accordance with the Contingency Plan, minimizing risk to human health and the environment.  Response time for control and clean up was approximately six hours.  By promptly reacting, this incident did not threaten the environment or human health outside the facility.
column169: This incident was discussed and Rail car Operations training was conducted on April 22, 2016.

HE UTILIZED HIS DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE INFORMATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, HE ALTERED HIS PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. HE CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. HE SWEPT THE FLOOR AROUND THE AREA TO ENSURE THAT NO POWDER WAS LEFT BEHIND AND ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. THEN HE TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN WE OPENED THE BOX, WE FOUND THAT THE POWDER HAD COME FROM A LOOSE SEAL ON THE LID OF THE 25LB PAIL.
column169: PLACE CONTAINER INTO PLASTIC BAG   SEAL BEFORE PLACING IT IN THE BOX. USE CUSHIONING TO ENSURE THE PRODUCT STAYS IN PLACE.

SUMMARY-  MCA Tanker 1913 arrived at the consignee with a leak where the spool is welded and the flange outlet is connected. This Tanker was modified by an outside vendor and this was the first load hauled, since the modifications.  Unloading personnel determined product had crystallized around the weld, on the spool attached to the external, off loading flange valve. The tanker was staged in the consignee's unloading bay, secured over a spill collection/containment area, while temporary repairs could be arranged. Temporary repairs were performed and the tanker was returned to the shipper.    SPILL/RELEASE-   SODIUM BICARBONATE was placed on the spool around the crystallized product.  No product was released other than what formed around the spool.

column168: On 04/25/2016 at 1432 hours personnel in the CSXT Acca yard discovered DBUX 303050, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S. leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and (Abengoa Bioenergy, VA DEM and CHEMTRECT) were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2016-0420-00229. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the sample line was open and the secondary closure plug was not in place. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Brad, Abengoa Bioenergy). Contractor personnel fixed the problem and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 145 - Sample Line Leaked    5 (5 + 3 + 0) X ( 2 + 0 ) = 80 NARRI

NAR Cause Code: 208 Manway, Hinged + Bolted    5 ( 5 + 5 + 3) X ( 2 + 0 ) = 80 NARRI

column168: Transport driver was traveling southbound on Hwy 96 when a vehicle ahead also traveling southbound struck a cow crossing the road.  The transport driver attempted to avoid striking another cow attempting to cross the road and overturned the transport truck.  Subsequently, a 3rd party vehicle traveling northbound collided into the cab of the truck.  The cargo tank breached all five compartments at the weld seams as a result of the tank overturning and skidding on the asphalt roadway. The fire department and emergency crews responded and quickly controlled the scene and contained the release.  An environmental remediation company was secured to clean up the spilled fuel, excavate contaminated soil and transport waste generated to appropriate disposal facilities.
column169: Train drivers to be prepared for unexpected wildlife and other animals that may enter the roadway especially after dark.  Train drivers to not attempt to avoid an animal strike that may cause them to loose control of the vehicle.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Incompatible Product
column168: TCIX 165029 was discovered leaking from the bottom outlet valve on Saturday, April 9, 2016 at 10:54 hours. The tank car contained 50% sodium hydroxide solution and was shipped from Formosa Plastics, USA in Point Comfort, TX. Upon notification of the leak, PTRA contacted M&M Protection. PTRA Safety Officer and M&M Protection responders arrived on scene at approximately 11:00 hours. After getting additional personnel on scene and conducting a safety briefing M&M sent a team into the area to inspect the car and determine the cause of the leak and attempt to stop the flow of product. By the time they were able to begin stopping the flow the car had emptied all contents. Inspection of the valve indicated that the internal 4 inch bottom outlet valve was locked and sealed in the open position. The secondary 2 inch valve assembly had a threaded cap which was determined to be made of aluminum instead of steel. The sodium hydroxide solution reacted with the aluminum and corroded through the valve cap assembly until the assembly failed and began discharging product to the ground.  Approximately 15100 gallons of product was discharged onto the ground in the PTRA American yard. Remediation efforts are ongoing. The NRC, CHEMTREC and TCEQ were notified of the incident within two hours of being on scene. Formosa Plastics was notified as well.
column169: FORMOSA Plastics is investigating the cause of the failures for the improper secondary valve assembly and the internal ball valve being shipped in the open position.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER ON 4/6/16 AT BAY 11 IN THE UNLOAD. UPON ARRIVAL I INSPECTED THE BOX AND REALIZED THAT IT WAS AN UNDECLARED CORROSIVE HAZMAT. I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE WHICH LEAD ME TO THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, I USED THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE THEN USED THE APPROPRIATE PPE. AFTER I GOT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED IN A LINED SPILL TRAY, I TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO THE DMP AREA. THEN I GOT MY DISTRICT CHSP SUPERVISOR BRIAN SPENCER. THEN I GOT THE INFORMATION I NEEDED TO PROCESS THE HAZMAT, I CUT OFF ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD AND PACKAGING MATERIAL AND PLACED IT IN THE GREEN BAG. THEN FINISHED CONTAINING EVERYTHING IN THE BAG AND GOOSE NECKED THE BAG. FINALLY I STARTED PROCESSING THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT.
column169: USE PROPER SHIPPING HAZMAT LABELS/SHIPPING PAPERS. USE PROPER PACKING AND PACKING MATERIAL. USE PROPER PACKING HANDLING AND FOLLOW ORIENTATION ARROWS.

LEAK WAS DETECTED WHILE AT TRUCK STOP OFF HIGHWAY 19 IN MY NEBO WV. RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT, INSIDE TRAILER AND ON TRACTOR ITSELF. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERED THE STAY DRY AND FREE THREATENED BY THE RELEASE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL PROCEEDED TO OFFLOAD THE TRAILER, CLEAN TRAILER FLOOR AND TRACTOR AND CONTAINERIZE ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS. ASPHALT LOT AND TRAILER WERE PRESSURE WASHED TO REMOVED RESIDUAL AND ALL WASH TANK WAS PLUGGED AND UPRIGHTED TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE AND LOAD WAS SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: DURING THE OFF LOADING AT POINT WEST- STAKER THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF THE DRIVER SIDE AND HEARD A DUST CAP POP OFF FROM THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE VEHICLE AND PRODUCT SPRAYING FROM THAT SIDE OF THE TRUCK. DRIVER QUICKLY SHUT PUMPING DOWN AND PLACED A SPARE CAP ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE PIPING TO CONTAIN PRODUCT FROM LEAKING. THE DRIVER THEN CALLED DISPATCH TO LET THEM KNOW OF THE INCIDENT AND ESTIMATED ABOUT 20 GALLONS WAS RELEASED. THE DRIVER HAD ENOUGH TO ABSORB AND COLLECT THAT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON HIS TRUCK. THE NEXT DAY I RECEIVED A CALL THAT THERE WAS STILL MORE PRODUCT ON SITE AND NEEDED TO BE CLEANED UP. STAKER CALLED THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL TEAM DOWN AND ADVISED US MORE ON THE SITUATION. THEIR TEAM ESTIMATED ABOUT 50-60 GALLONS WAS MORE ACCURATE, AND IT RAN DOWNHILL INTO THE CONTAINMENT AND PUDDLED THERE. WE THEN CALLED A VAC-TRUCK TO COLLECT THE PUDDLE FROM THE CONTAINMENT, AND STAKER'S TEAM WE AUTHORIZED TO PULL SAMPLES AND DO THE EXCAVATION OF THE SOILS AND SENT TO DISPOSAL.
column169: IN THIS SITUATION WITH THIS BEING AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE, WE INVESTIGATED THE VALVE AND FOUND THAT THE PSI RATING IS 75 PSI AND WITH OUR PUMPS AT AN IDLE IS AT 175 PSI. WE HAVE CONTACTED THE MANUFACTURER AND SHOWED THEM OUR FINDINGS. WE ARE PURCHASING NEW VALVE'S THAT MEET THE SPECIFICATION AND WE ARE RUNNING A CAMPAIGN TO HAVE THEM REPLACED ASAP

column168: The employee was filling one of two tanks at a customer location and moved his vehicle around to position to fill the other tank. He noticed that he did not have an order for the other tank and called into the acting operation manager to see if an order was forthcoming. He connected the filler hose to the tank and waited inside his truck as it was raining. When the decision was made not to fill the second tank, the driver closed his truck door and pulled away, not realizing the hose was still connected. The employee was not injured. 8 gallons of propane dissipated into the air. The only damage was to the hose and another hose has been ordered.
column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control & performing a complete walk around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write & present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A Pull-Away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: On or about April 6th, 2016, AALA offered a shipment containing a hazardous material UN3356, Oxygen Generator, Chemical 5.1, for air transportation in commerce from Tulsa, Oklahoma to Los Angeles, California (AWB# 001TUL13492931.  The undeclared company material (COMAT) shipment was accepted and transported on passenger aircraft which is forbidden.     Oxygen generators are forbidden for shipment on passenger aircraft and AALA has all oxygen generators and higher assemblies containing oxygen generators flagged as hazardous materials in the inventory system as well as forbidden for shipment in the shipping system HazRaps.  The Aircraft On Ground (AOG) desk Material Logistic Specialist (MLS) shipper did not observe the hazmat communication provided to inform the employee that the part is a hazardous material nor follow the process and procedure on moving the oxygen generator to the designated shipping location.
column169: Stock of the oxygen generators will be stored in a designated area.  This area will have markings located on the shelves identifying these items as hazardous items.  Employee was counseled and required to retake the hazmat recurrent training.  Task specific training will be implemented which will provide training in advance of job assignment.  Develop a standard operating process (SOP) for applying the green hazmat sticker on all hazmat items.

column168: On April 7, 2016, truck tractor No. 826 was pulling tanker trailer No.152 loaded with 13,400 gallons of gasoline, traveling east on Highway M-60. There are 5 compartments in the trailer with the following capacities (gal.): 1-4,800; 2-1199; 3-1800; 4-3000; 5-3000. The compartments contained the following amount of gasoline (gal.): 1-4700; 2-1150; 3-1750; 4-2900; 5-2900.  At the Y intersection of Pine Lake Road, M-60 makes a left curve. For unknown reasons, the vehicle and trailer left the roadway causing the complete unit to roll over, crushing and ripping open compartment #1 and spilling 4,700 gallons of gasoline onto the ground. The unit came to rest, laying on the left (driver's) side of the vehicle. Additionally, the rollover caused the probe in the dome lid of compartment #3 to be unseated, releasing 717 gallons from that compartment. The Cass County Sheriff Patrol Division was the first emergency responder on scene. Additionally, five (5) fire departments responded to the scene, laying down a foam blanket to mitigate the possibility of ignition. Brenner Oil Company's Safety Supervisor was on-site at 03:50.  The driver was pronounced deceased and the procedure to pump off the remaining product was begun.      The first environmental response company at the scene was Inserv Industrial Services (514 E. Marion St., Mishawaka, IN).      The total property damage, response costs, and remediation costs are not yet available.

column168: On April 26, 2016, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer when 2-5 gallon pails of UN1263, Super 16 Gun Cleaner, 3, II was discovered to be damaged. It appeared that the pails were damaged due to a forklift puncture. Approximately 5 gallons of product was immediately released to the trailer floor. Contractor used absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor generated 1-55 gallon poly drum of impacted absorbents, debris, and damaged pails to be profiled and approved for disposal.

CMV driver heading westbound on Centerville road took eyes off road, vehicle right side tires left paved portion of road into shoulder which was 8" below level of pavement. column169: Additional training on distracted driving and rollover prevention.

column168: At point of unloading, Pressure Relief Valve found to be bubbling. Vapor escaping. Response put wet blanket over it, and trailer unloaded. Trailer taken to a repair facility.It was found that an Internal baffle had broken loose and hit the pressure relief valve, bending it slightly allowing vapor to escape. Baffle repaired. New pressure relief valve installed. Trailer released for duty.

column168: While loading a shipment of hazardous waste at the customer's site, a 15 gallon plastic container dropped while stacking it on the drum dolly.  The driver picked it up and cleaned up the spilled material with absorbent pads which he placed into the container.  He did not report the incident at the time to his supervisor.  The customer called the office and reported the incident while requesting that we return to assess the damage and do further clean up.
column169: The driver was terminated for failure to report the incident and to follow proper spill cleanup protocol.

column168: Approximately 4 oz. of UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid released from a 55 gallon poly drum due to a faulty bung cap. The release has impacted only the top of the drum and was confined to the inside of the trailer. A contractor responded to perform cleanup activities. (1) 55 gallon poly drum containing neutralized acid and absorbent was generated for disposal.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN LOWER REWRAP. INSPECTION OF THE LEAKER REVEALED THAT THE SEAL ON THE METAL CONTAINER WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED. IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKAGE IS MISSING THE REQUIRED CLASS 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL ON THE OUTER CONTAINER.
column169: FIRST, HAVE SHIPPER CHECK TO MAKE SURE CAPS ARE SECURELY TIGHTENED ON THE CONTAINER BEFORE SHIPPING. SECOND, THE AUDITOR AT THE ORIGIN SHOULD HAVE NOT ACCEPTED THIS PACKAGE INTO THE SYSTEM, SINCE IT IS MISSING THE DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL.

column168: TWO 2.5 GALLON BOTTLES ONE LEAKED AT THE CLOSURE

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE UNLOADER AT DOOR 16 IN UNLOAD-B. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE DAMAGED, PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS AREA SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 1 MIN A 12 HR RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER REFERRING TO THE DECISION TREE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGED PKG WAS CONTAINED (NO RELEASE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/4 ROTATION, CREATING A BREACH FOR APPROX. 8 OZ OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM, CONTAMINATING THE SIDE WALL OF THE CARTON. THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQUARE IN BURSTING TEST. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A CORRUGATED DIVIDER.

column168: CALLED TO PD-1, FOUND PACKAGE IN CHUTE WITH A SOILED BOX. FOLLOWED DMP PROCEDURES, CLEANED UP SPILL, RETURNED TO DMP FOR FURTHER. PROCESSING.

PART-TIME SUPERVISOR CALLED FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE. I TOOK A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART, GOT TO THE AREA, SET UP MY 15 FOOT HOT ZONE AND LOOKED AT MY DECISION TREE AND NOTICE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT LABEL AND READ THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET THE TOOK BACK TO DMP AS FAST AS POSSIBLE.

AN EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING AN IRREG TRAIN BETWEEN BOXLINES 5 6 WHEN A HAZMAT PACKAGE FELL OFF OF ONE OF THE CARTS AND STARTED TO LEAK ON THE FLOOR. THE SUPERVISOR SAW IT IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. ELONDA RESPONDED TO THE CALL. SHE UTILIZED HER DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. SHE CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. SHE USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR. SHE SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT   ADDED IT TO THE LINED SPILL TRAY. THEN SHE TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREAFOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD CRACKED THE LIQUID HAD SOILED 5 OTHER BOTTLES.

Driver pulled into consignee facility, had operations at the facility unlock the lock to the 2 on site stationary storage tanks inside their building. Operations instructed driver to unload into the storage tank which was capable of holding the full amount of the shipment. Driver proceeded to open the valve to a different storage tank which could not hold the product, result was overfill of the storage tank into contained area inside the building. There were no injuries or environmental impact due to the overflow of the storage tank. There was NO package failure, the transportation equipment functioned properly, the incident was caused by driver error.    The release was contained and cleaned up by the consignee with no further issue noted. There was no release to the environment noted.
column169: There was no issue with the cargo tank or equipment, which performed as expected. The driver was counseled. and the standard operating procedure is under review, with provisions in the current draft to provide additional review prior and during unloading to prevent recurrence.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: CTS NATIONAL CORPORATION DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON I-44, WEST OF US 50, IN THE RIGHT LANE. TWO OTHER TRACTOR TRAILERS WERE IN THE RIGHT LANE IN FRONT OF THE CTS NATIONAL CORPORATION VEHICLE AND BOTH HAD SLOWED DUE TO TRAFFIC CONGESTION CAUSED BY A CONSTRUCTION ZONE AHEAD. THE CTS NATIONAL CORPORATION DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO BRAKE AND SLOW AS HE APPROACHED THE OTHER TWO VEHICLES. HE WAS UNABLE TO STOP, SO HE MERGED INTO THE LEFT LANE TO AVOID THE VEHICLES. THE RIGHT SIDE TRAILER OF THE CTS NATIONAL CORPORATION VEHICLE STRUCK THE LEFT REAR TRAILER OF THE FIRST TRACTOR TRAILER AHEAD OF IT IN THE RIGHT LANE. BOTH OF THESE UNITS CAUGHT FIRE AT THIS POINT. THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT PUSHED THE SECOND TRACTOR TRAILER INTO THE REAR OF THE THIRD TRACTOR TRAILER. THE FIRE CONSUMED THE ENTIRE CTS NATIONAL CORPORATION VEHICLE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTING PAINT THAT IS CLASSIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE COLLISION CAUSED SOME OF THE CONTAINERS TO FAIL RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.   FIRE, EMS AND POLICE WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. EMS TRANSPORTED ONE PERSON TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. THE MISSOURI STATE POLICE INVESTIGATED THE ACCIDENT. THE MISSOURI DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. THE MISSOURI DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATIONS TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE TO CONTROL AND CLEANUP THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASED. ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATIONS CLEANED UP THE RELEASE AND ARRANGED FOR DISPOSAL OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. tanker was in the process of loading when a leaking gasket was discovered at the inlet valve. The driver shut down the loading process and notified facility personnel and local dispatch. A Clean Harbors response crew responded to the scene, donned the proper PPE and remediated the impacted areas of the trailer and ground below the trailer. The waste generated during the cleanup process was properly containerized for future disposal. The inlet valve gasket was replaced and the tanker was put back into service. CDPHE duty officer Lyle Moore was notified via telephone. No report number provided due to the release being below the RQ per Lyle Moore.
column169: Prior to the time the tanker was loaded for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. The inlet valve gasket was removed, inspected and replaced. A pressure test was performed with no leakage. The tanker was then returned to service.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On April 13th, 2016, the GATX 49525 was found to have a white solid residue on the outside jacket of the tank car while in Great Falls, MT.  The car was isolated and inspected by BNSF Hazmat/Mechanical personnel and the white material was found to have a pH of 12.5.  Further inspection revealed that the rupture disk on the pressure relief device had ruptured allowing NaOH to release through the burst disk.  Crews removed the bad rupture disk, cleaned the sealing area and replaced with an in kind rupture disk.  Contract responders arrived to clean and neutralize the exterior of the car.  Once the car was cleaned, it was released back into transportation and allowed to continue to offload.
column169: BNSF is continuing to investigate this incident and work with local Operations on handling practices for switching operations at the Great Falls, MT rail yard.  Shippers should ensure proper and recommended inspection and replacement schedules for rupture disk devices are in place.

column168: ON ARPIL 11 2016 THE SWITCH CREW NOTICED THAT THE GATX 16221 HAD RELEASED ASPHALT AFTER FLAT SWITCHING THE RAIL CAR IN GREAT FALLS MT RAILYARD. THE CREW REPORTED A RELEASE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND THAT IT WAS ONLY A ONE-TIME RELEASE AND WAS NOT AACTIVELY LEAKING. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND INSPECTED BY BNSF HAZMAT/MECHANICAL EMPLOYEES AND FOUND TO HAVE RELEASED ASPHALT THROUGH THE INTACT PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE VALVE WAS STILL INTACT AND THE CAR STILL HAD PRESSURE ON IT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A HYDRAULIC SURGE OF LIQUID ASPHALT HAD ACTIVATED THE RELIEF VALVE. THE VALVE THEN RECLOSED AS INTENDED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND SENT AN RERESENATATIVE TO THE RAILYARD TO INSPECT THE CAR. AN OTMA WAS OBTAINED BY THE SHIPPER TO HAVE THE CAR RETUNED FOR VALVE REPLACEMENT AND INSPECTION AT THEIR FACILITY. THE OTMA WAS OBTAINED ON 4/15/16 AND THE CAR MOVED BACK TO CALUMET
column169: BNSF is continuing to investigate the cause of this incident. Ensure the package and components are in proper working condition as specified forthe packaging. Debrief with local Rail operations to review and re-brief on coupling speed limitations for cars.

column168: AT 09:30 ON 4/12/16 LARS ADVISED THAT UNIT CONTAINING HAZMAT WAS OBSERVED LEAKING A WHITE SUBSTANCE UPON DERAMP AT THE STOCKTON INTERMODAL FACILITY. ERTS WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF LEAK. ERTS DISPACHTED PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL TO INSPECT AND REMEDIATE. PATRIOT ARRIVE ONSITE AT APPROXIMATELY 11:45 AND BEGAN CLEAN UP OF RAIL CAR AND INSPECTION OF TRAILER. CONTRACTOR COMPLETED REMEDIATION AT APPROX 17:30. LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND PLACED BACK INTO UNIT. HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM FACILITY AND DISPOSED OF BY CONTRACTOR. INTERIOR INSPECTION OF TRAILER REVEALED A HAZMAT SHIPMENT OF MIXED PRODUCT CONTAINING MENTAL IBC TOTES OF WHITE INK DRUMS OF WHITE INK RESTING ON PALLETS, AND CARTONIZED CARGO ON PALLETS. LOAD WAS CONFIGURED IN TWO ROW WITH A SECOND LAYER RESTING ON EAT TRACK BARS THROUGHOUT. LOAD WAS SECURED WITH MULTIPLE AIRBAGS. IN ORDER TO DETERMINE SOURCE OF LEAK UNITS WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED. THE LEAK WAS IDENTIFIED MID WAY INTO THE TRAILER ON THE RIGHT SIDE AND CONSISTED OF A PALLET OF FOUR DRUMS. ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE UNDERSIDE. CLOSER INSPECTION OF THIS DRUM REVEALED A SPLIT IN THE BOTTOM OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH IN LENGTH. NO SIGNS WERE VISIBLE THAT THIS DRUM CAME IN CONTACT WITH A FOREIGN OBJECT AND NO FRICTION MARKINGS WERE VISIBLE FROM THE OUTSIDE. ALL DID APPEAR AS IF THEY WERE REAL CONDITIONED AND HAD MULTIPLE DENTS ON THE UNDER SIDE.
column169: SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED WITH THE DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT FOR APPROPRIATE INVESTIGATION AND FOLLOW-UP.

Acid loader overfilled the center compartment cargo tank and approximately 200 pounds (15 gallons)spilled out the top dome. column169: 1. The acid loader has received additional training.  2. Added compartment capacity labels to the top of cargo tank. Usually load single compartment cargo tanks.  4. Operating procedures will be revised to provide additional clarification.

At the NEMF terminal in Tonowanda, NY, a 300 gallon metal tote that had an electric pump mounted to its top released approximately 5 gallons of UN2920 Nalcon 7648.  The release came from the pump hoses that were not properly drained/purged prior to shipping.  The release was contained to a plastic containment bin in which the tote was shipped. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to collect the released material and properly drain/purge the pump hoses.  The waste was collected into poly drums and taken for proper disposal.

column168: Driver was executing a left hand turn from Moody Bld to Northbound A1A in Flagler Beach, FL when the tote move to the rear of the truck allowing the strap to come completely loose and fall from the flatbed straight truck.  Surveillance video obtained from a nearby business shows the tote slide to the rear and the top to the tote appears to fail underneath the strap before the tote falls from the truck.  We suspect a smaller tote which was being secured by the same strap allowed for the movement    The driver and a nearby Public Works employee began containing the spill.  In approx. 4-10 minutes local police and fire were on scene and had isolated the area.  St. John's County Hazmant Response team was brought in and they applied approx 50lbs of Sodium Bicarbonate to neutralize.  Meantime Hawkins dispatched an employee with a pallet of Sodium Bicarbonate and contacted SWS Environmental out of Jacksonville to respond to the incident.  Hawkins employee arrived first and ad the entire pallet of bicarbonate was used to further neutralize the acid.  SWS arrived at approximately 1300 hrs and began cleanup operations.  Sand and soil were removed until neutral soil was found.  Approx 28 yards in total were removed from the site.  The site was then back-filled with a sand specified by FL DEQ agent on scene. The majority of the clean up operations were completed by 2230  with all equipment and material removed the operation were and the "OK" given to SWS contractors around 1530 on 4/22/2016
column169: Hawkins is taking a two fold approach at preventing another incident like this in the future.  We are working with tote manufacturers and reviewing tote storing and handling practices in FL.  The goal is to improve tote performance by limiting UV exposure where possible, while possibly setting a "sunset" date for totes used in particular service.     The second method is we are evaluating tote securement practices involving flatbed/stakebed trucks.  Once a preferred method of securement is identified, that standard will be communicated to all company operators who operate similar vehicles.

column168: On April 18, 2016, RDWY 131380 arrived leaking at San Bernardino IBU. Patriot Environmental was dispatched to re-mediate the leak at the facility. The leak was identified to be originating at midpoint of the container which consisted of a pallet of four (4) 55 gallon drums. One of the 55 gallon drums, leaked approximately 25 gallons of Sun Chemical product, UN 1210, PG II, flammable printing ink from the underside. Upon close inspection of the drum, it revealed a split at the bottom of approximately 1 1/2 inch in length. No visible signs that the 55 gallon drum came in contact with a foreign object and no friction markings were visible on the outside. All drums did appear to be reconditioned or overpack shipping drums that had multiple dents on the exterior.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure that their drums (packaging) meet shipping standards. This is the second case in one week from the same shipper and a leaking drum of printer ink. The shipper is using refurbished drums which are not suitable for shipping product and are failing during transportation. If refurbished drums are continued to be used in the shipping and packaging of product, stricter quality control standards need to be enforced.

column168: On April 23, 2016 at 14:04 hours CSXT train dispatcher advised that a passing Norfolk Southern Railroad crew had reported UTLX 203989, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., was suspected to be venting from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Renewable Products Marketing Group, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2016-0423-00092).  Marion Environmental Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product leaking from a threaded connection between the tank cars liquid line and the liquid line valve mounting flange.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative (Jason Wojahn).  MEI attempted to tighten the threaded connection, however, it was discovered that inadequate clearance between the liquid line valves mounting flange and a separate blind flange on the tank cars pressure plate would not allow proper securement.  In order to prevent further release of product, MEI removed the tank cars liquid line valve and installed a threaded valve which afforded the necessary clearance for tightening.  Because MEI is neither a certified or registered mobile repair unit, and the valve installed is not a DOT/AAR compliant valve; the car is being held out of transportation until such time as the car owner can arrange the necessary repairs and/or obtain a One Time Move Approval from the FRA.   NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause Code: 282

column168: TILX 191856 was in the yard in Klamath Falls, OR.  A carman noticed some liquid running down the side of the car. A BNSF responder ascended the car, opened the combination housing and found the liquid valve to be less than tool tight. Upon further investigation, it was noted that the liquid valve seemed to have been loosened up so the lid for the combination housing would clear the valve handle when closed. The responder was able to tighten the liquid valve another 120 degrees, successfully tightening the valve, stopping the release, and able to close the lid to the combination housing. Released product of approximately 1/2 gallon evaporated.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure proper tightening of all valves. Proper securing and attention to detail will prevent further releases of hazardous materials in the future.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, THE ERGON TRUCKING VEHICLE WAS OVERFILLED, WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL. FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE DIRT PARKING LOT, ADJACENT GRASSY SHOULDER, AND RAN INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH. ERGON TRUCKING PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED ABSORBENT BOOM TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT WITHIN THE DITCH, AND PREVENT MIGRATION. WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER THE FREE PRODUCT FROM IMMEDIATE AREA AND IMPACTED DRAINAGE DITCH. WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL ALSO EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOIL AND GRASS FROM THE AREA, AND SWAPPED OUT EXISTING ABSORBENT BOOM. APPROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS OF OIL AND WATER WERE RECOVERED FROM THE DRAINAGE DITCH, AND ONE ROLL OFF OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND ABSORBENTS WAS GENERATED. BOOM MAINTENANCE WAS PERFORMED, FOLLOWING PERIODIC RAINFALL, TO ENSURE ALL CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: ERGON TRUCKING INC. WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

THE MATERIAL IS LOADED AT AN EXTREMELY FAST PACE AND SOLIDIFIES ALMOST IMMEDIATELY WHEN OUTSIDE THE TANKER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FAULTY UNLOADING VALVE. ONCE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED OFF TRAILER, IT WAS BROUGHT TO HAZMAT'S YARD, A SHORT DISTANCE FROM THE SHIPPER SITE, AND EXAMINED BY SHOP PERSONNEL. column169: THE ENTIRE VALVE ASSEMBLY WAS REPLACED. THIS TRAILER IS THE ONLY ONE DEDICATED TO THE SULFUR MOLTEN MATERIAL.

column168: ON APRIL 6, 2016 A LIQUID TRANSPORT TANKER TRAILER CARRYING UN1230 METHANOL WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE VEHICLE INCIDENT WHERE THE TRAILER BECAME UNHOOKED FROM THE TRACTOR, FELL TO THE GROUND ON THE HIGHWAY AND SLID TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. A DRIVER ASSISTANCE COMPANY SAW THE TRAILER DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRACTOR AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911 FOR POLICE/FIRE ASSISTANCE. DRIVER CONTACTED LIQUID TRANSPORT TERMINAL MANAGER, RICHARD BURLOCK AND CONTACTED LAZER TOWING FOR ASSISTANCE. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE BUT THE DOLLY LEGS AND THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER WERE DAMAGED. THE INTEGRITY OF THE CARGO TANK HOLDING THE LIQUID WAS NOT COMPROMISED; THEREFORE NO LEAKING OF THE PRODUCT. THE 5TH WHEEL WAS INSPECTED WHEN THE TRUCK WAS DRIVEN BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE 5TH WHEEL MECHANISM WAS NOT DEFECTIVE OR DAMAGED. RATHER THE PROBLEM WAS THAT THE DRIVER DID NOT PROPERLY CONNECT THE KING PIN ON THE CARGO TANK TO THE 5TH WHEEL OF THE TRACTOR. THIS WAS A HUMAN ERROR ISSUE. REGARDLESS FOR PRECAUTIONARY ISSUES, THE 5TH WHEEL WAS VOLUNTARILY REPLACED WITH A NEW 5TH WHEEL.
column169: THE 5TH WHEEL INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS VOLUNTARILY REMOVED AND REPLACED. THE DRIVER RECEIVED MANDATORY RETRAINING ON HOW TO CONNECT A TRAILER TO A TRACTOR. ADDITIONALLY THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS A TRAINING TOOL FOR ALL DRIVERS IN THE 3RD QUARTER 2016 SAFETY MEETING MATERIAL AT ALL TERMINALS.

column168: A group of 6 Cudd Pressure Control commercial motor vehicles were headed back to their Krebs, OK yard after completion of a job in Kearney, MO. They exited off US-69 south of Fort Scott, KS and followed a parallel road: Kansas State Highway 7. K-7 is a lane state highway without an improved shoulder and steep ditches that is primarily oriented North and South. At approx. 0625 a CPCI employee driving a Nitrogen transport at the rear of the convoy was heading southbound on K-7. The tractor was traveling approx. 55-65 mph, when the passenger side rear trailer tires dropped off the roadway into the west ditch. The employee traveled approx. 200 ft. partially off the roadway as the weight of the trailer pulled the rig deeper into the ditch, causing the truck to begin rotating in a counterclockwise direction. The employee attempted to regain control of the vehicle, but over corrected caused the tractor to travel in a perpendicular motion to the intended direction of travel. The high level of inertia in the original travel path shifted the COG, which exceeded the tractors roll over threshold, resulting in the rig overturning and sliding approx. 60 ft before coming to a stop. Based on the skid marks on the road it is estimated that the rig was traveling  40-45mph when it overturned.  The supervisor for the group organized traffic control and the driver assistance in climbing out of the vehicle and contacted 911. During the overturn of the N2 cargo tank, the pressure relief valve was broken allowing free release of N2. The 85 gallons dispersed into the atmosphere relatively quickly, before the arrival of the Kansas Highway Patrol to the scene. Following Kansas protocol, notifications to Kansas City resulted in dispatched emergency responders who had to arrive to release the vehicle. This delay caused the extended highway closure as the tractor trailer lay across the 2 lanes of the roadway. Vehicle was righted, and towed from the scene. Environmental clean-up contractor acting on the behalf of CPCI removed 2-55 gallon drums of Absorbents used to collect motor oil, antifreeze and diesel fuel that dripped from the over turned truck tractor.  The protocols of the State of Kansas prevented trained subject matter experts, who were immediately present, from advising and coordinating removal of the unit from the roadway. This is another example of a significant incident being influenced by subjective factors that were not caused by a release, but only the perceived threat to trained individuals.
column169: 1. Incident Investigation to be shared across the company.  2. Incident will be reviewed in region wide safety meeting.

column168: A Veolia employee was transferring material from truck to truck at the Livonia, MI 10-day in-transit facilty located at 11681 Levan Road. The employee noticed a small puddle underneath a pallet. After moving the pallet, the employee identified a small pin hole on the bottom of a drum that was on the pallet. The drum contained a microbiocide and was shipped as UN3265, Waste Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Organic, N.O.S.(5-Chloro-2-Methyl-4-ISOThiazolin-3-One, 2-Methyl-3(2H)- Isothiazolone), 8, II, RQ(D002). It was estimated that approximately three ounces was released. The spill was cleaned up using absorbent pads which were placed into the salvage drum that the drum was placed into.
column169: The investigation revealed that the material was placed into a newly purchased reconditioned closed head steel drum about one week prior to the shipment. The incident was reviewed with field personnel. Although there were no obvious protruding nails on this pallet, the emphasis was to ensure when placing drums onto pallets to be sure to verify that there are no nails protruding from the pallet prior to placing the drum onto it.

column169: SWRR IS IMPLEMENTING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES TO IMPROVE MECHANICAL INSPECTIONS.

column168: Approximately 30 gallons of UN3082 "Araldite GY 6010 US" leaked from the dome lid on a DOT307 due to damage caused by a single vehicle rollover accident. The vehicle rolled onto it's passenger side. The release impacted an area of grassy soil measuring approximately 25' x 5' adjacent to the roadway. A contractor responded and conducted a transfer of the material into a relief tanker. The impacted soil was excavated immediately after the vehicle was off loaded and removed from the site. All waste was containerized and transported off site for disposal.

column168: Container was reported leaking by driver. After inspection 13 drums were found to be leaking in various locations. Cause of leak appears to be deterioration of the drum itself.
column169: Worked with manufacture and over packed all 13 leaking drums. The entire shipment of 80 drums was transported back to facility to perform inspection on drums.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: Mechanical personnel reported product venting from top of the car.  Upon inspection, car was noted with the quick fill hole cover gasket to be mis-positioned on the quick fill hole nozzle.  Further inspection revealed the gasket to be worn, and stretched out of shape. A temporary Gortex gasket was positioned so that the car could be secured from release and spotted for further handling.  On 4-25-16, the shipper dispatched Rescar Mobile Rail Repair to replace the Gortex gasket with a Viton gasket. Additional exceptions noted, all 4 placards were missing and the commodity name stenciled on the left and right sides of the car were covered with magnetic tape.  The car had recently been shopped, inspected and repainted in February 2016.  Upon correction of all noted exceptions, car was released for transportation.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: PACKAGE WAS WET FROM INSIDE OUT. DISCOVERED AT CAR DURING PRELOAD. WE STOPPED THE PROGRESS AND A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ADDRESSED PKG. LIQUID SHOE POLISH (4 OZ BOTTLE) LEAKED DUE TO BROKEN CAP ONTO OTHER ITEMS. AT THAT TIME, THE OTHER CONTENTS OF THE PKG WERE INSPECTED AND TWO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE DISCOVERED. ONE (ONE GALLON) METAL BOTTLE OF ALL-PURPOSE CEMENT, AND ONE (ONE GALLON) METAL BOTTLE OF ALL-PURPOSE THINNER. A SECOND RESPONDER LOOKED UP THE MSDS OF THESE ITEMS AS THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OF ANY KIND TO INDICATE THEY WERE HAZARDOUS. THE MSDS INDICATED THESE WERE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, CLASS 3 AND SHOULD HAVE PROPER IDENTIFICATION MARKINGS. I CALLED SHAWN MACPHERSON TO VALIDATE. HE AGREED WITH MY DETERMINATION AND INSTRUCTED ME TO HOLD THE PACKAGE AND PROCEED WITH THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT PROCEDURES. AGAIN, NO HAZMAT LIQUID LEAKED, THE HAZMATS WERE DISCOVERED AFTER RESPONDING TO A NON-HAZMAT MATERIAL.

column168: PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP FROM THE SHIPPER VIA UPS DRIVER AND WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE BUILDING. WHEN THE PACKAGE CAR THAT CONTAINED THIS PACKAGE WAS BEING UNLOADED, THE PACKAGE MADE ITS WAY TO THE BACK OF THE BUILDING AND THAT'S WHEN IT WAS SPOTTED LEAKING. WHEN I RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGE I NOTICE THAT THE PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS ON IT BUT COULD SMELL GASOLINE/FUEL. I OPEN THE BOX AND THERE WAS SOME SORT OF FUEL HOLDING TANK THAT WAS A LEAST 3 GALLONS BIG AND STILL HAD FUEL INSIDE OF IT AND WAS LEAKING OUT. THIS SHIPMENT HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal a drum was discovered leaking inside the trailer. After further investigation, it was determined that the drum was punctured by another drum loaded in front of it. The drum was immediately placed into an over-pack along with absorbent materials for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had there been adequate dunnage placed between the drums. This incident may be used as an example in future training discussions to demonstrate the importance of proper blocking and bracing techniques.

All waste was containerized for disposal. The damaged drum was over packed.

column168: 1 DRUM 19L CAO RFL PG II , was damaged with a forklift blade at Forward Air in Columbus ohio. Forward Air ( trucking) turned the leaking drum upside to stop the leakage and wrapped the drum in shrinkwrap , and shrinkwrapped the drum to a skid. The intenetion was to hold at CMH but Forward Air sent to shipment to Forward Air at ORD , which delivered the shipment to Lufthansa Cargo at ORD.  Lufthansa Cargo noted damaged to the drum upon receipt , but did not discover leakage until the shrinwrap was revmoved from the skid, and then the shrinkwrap was removed from the drum.  Lufthansa Cargo placed the drum in a recovery drum and will have it properly disposed of as per shipper's disposition. The overpack skid the damaged/leaking drum came from had to be redone/repacked as some of the RFL DGR had leaked onto the inside of this overpack, this was done by Labelmaster ORD.   Lufthansa Cargo is still tring to obtain corrective action from Forward air to prevent leaking DGR from being transported to an airline.
column169: Lufthansa Cargo placed the drum in a recovery drum and will have it properly disposed of as per shipper's disposition. The overpack skid the damaged/leaking drum came from had to be redone/repacked as some of the RFL DGR had leaked onto the inside of this overpack, this was done by Labelmaster ORD.     Lufthansa Cargo is still tring to obtain corrective action from Forward air to prevent leaking DGR from being transported to an airline.     It was suggested to Forward to have an emergency response plan such as calling the local fire dept , and having recovery drums on site .     The forklift drivier was conseled by Forward Air to use utmost caution with Dangerous goods.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGING FAILURE. THIS LIKELY CAUSED PACKAGE RADIATION LEVELS TO EXCESS OF REGULATORY LIMITS. THE PACKAGE COULD HAVE BEEN OPENED ANYTIME AFTER HAVING BEEN PREPARED BY THE VARIAN SERVICE ENGINEER AT ST. column168: April 21, 2016 1150 pm Hub Manager reported trailer container RDWY133488 leaking a clear liquid and smoke coming out of the door seal. The Hub Manager was directed to segregate the container from the other containers in the area. A hazmat contractor was called to investigate.  April 22, 2016 0245 am Hazmat contractor arrived on-scene and after getting a situation update from the Terminal Manager proceeded to investigate the container which was still smoking. The Hazmat contractor tested the liquid which leaked from the container and found it to be acidic which agreed with the Corrosive placard on the side of the container. At this point the Hazmat contractor opened the door approximately six (6) inches and then half-way to gain access. Within approximately one minute of opening the door the contents of the container caught fire.  At 0255 am Fort Worth Fire arrived on scene and decided to keep the evacuation in place and let the fire burn until documentation of the container contents was confirmed.  At 0400 am BNSF and Fort Worth Fire decided to extinguish the fire with water and collect the runoff for characterization and disposal.  After the contents were cooled the contents were removed from the container and placed in roll-off dumpsters for characterization and disposal.  No employees or contractors were injured during this incident.
column169: Shippers should review loading and securement practices especially for hazardous materials shipments to prevent shifting of materials during movement.

column168: BNSF Mechanical, Tom St. Onge, reported a vapor release of Argon from railcar IAPX 1081 at Interbay Yard. The vapor release came from a pinhole leak in the return line from the exchanger system/pressure build on the bottom of the railcar. BNSF Mechanical stopped the leak by isolating the valve with direction from shipper.
column169: The shipper was notified and the request was made to the shipper to forward this information to those in charge of loading, maintenance and pre-trip inspections so they can review their procedures to prevent this from occurring in the future.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Was notified by yard personnel that UTLX 12708 was noted to have a slight drip of product down the side of the tank car. Upon arrival by the responders, product was noted coming from top of car. The responders climbed the car and found some pooling of product on top of the pressure plate and on top of the liquid line flange. Fill port was opened up to confirm liquid level which was at a proper level. Fill port was re-closed and sealed. The 2" plug cap on top of the liquid line was tool tight, but product noted around threads. The plug cap was removed and it was noted that there was no Teflon tape in place on the threads. Teflon tape was applied and the plug cap tool tightened.
column169: Shipper needs to confirm proper sealing of all threads, plugs, and valves prior to shipping product. Shipping procedures need to be evaluated and processes followed to ensure the release of a hazardous substance does not occur again.

column168: PACKAGE WAS LOADED INTO TRAILER. LOADER LOADED ANOTHER PALLET IN BEHIND AND INTO THE PLATTER OF DRUMS. CLEANING COMPOUND WAS SMELLED AND THE TRAILER UNLOADED TO THAT POINT. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED TO THE SIDE AND PATCHED. SPILL WAS CLEANED IMMEDIATELY.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR PROPER BRACING, SECURING, AND HANDLING OF FREIGHT TO INCLUDE SPECIFICALLY DRUMS AND TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 4/18/2016 RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM HUB PERSONNEL AT BSF LOS ANGELES THAT UNIT TEMZ 500344 WAS LEAKING A RED RESIN SUBSTANCE FROM THE REAR OF THE UNITS DOORS AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON SPILLED ONTO THE PLATFORM OF RAIL CAR TTAX 554022 WITH A FEW OUNCES OF PRODUCT SPILLING ON THE GROUND. THE TRAILER PLACARDING IDENTIFIED THE CARGO AS HAZARDOUS. REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED OUT TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND PERFORM AN ASSESSMENT AND CONFIRM THAT THE ACTUAL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS HAZARDOUS. INTERIOR INSPECTION FOUND UNIT TO BE LOADED WITH A MIX LOAD OF PALLETIZED CASED GOODS WITH RESIN LIKE PRODUCT COMING FROM THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. THE RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO ACCESS THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT AND FOUND A DAMAGED 5 GALLON BUCKET WITH A HOLE AND PRODUCT COMING OUT OF IT. THE LABEL ON THE BUCKET CLASSIFIED THE PRODUCT AS FLAMMABLE LIQUID CLASS 3 UN 1263 PAINT. THE RESPONDER WERE ABLE TO REMEDIATE THE TRAILER, RAILCAR AND ALL OTHER AFFECTED AREAS. SHIPMENT SEEMED TO HAVE SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT FROM IMPROPER SECUREMENT OF LOAD AND PACKAGE.

column168: A SMALL QTY (APPROXIMATELY 4 OZ) OF PRODUCT WAS DETECTED IN THE STAGING AREA WHERE THE TOTE WAS STORED OVERNIGHT. WHEN HE APPROACHED THE TRAILER HE NOTICED THAT MATERIAL WAS DRIPPING UNDER THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO PUT ON HIS PROPER PPE AND PUT DOWN THE ABSORBENT PADS AND ABSORBENT SOCK THAT HE HAD ON THE TRUCK. SWS WAS NOTIFIED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE TOTE WAS CRACKED ON THE LEFT FRONT SIDE, APPROXIMATELY MIDWAY. THE LEAK WAS NOT ABLE TO BE STOPPED UNTIL REACHED THE BOTTOM OF THE CRACK RESULTING IN ROUGHLY 1625 LBS/ 150 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED. SWS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE TOTE HAD BEEN TESTED AND PASSED INSPECTION ON 03/17/2016.
column169: CHECK STAGING AREA THOROUGHLY FOR ANY VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKING PRIOR TO LOADING TRAILER. ADD ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT PADS TO SPILL KITS TO HELP CONTAIN RELEASED PRODUCT.

column168: VEHICLE ONE TRAVELING NORTH ON LA520 WHEN IT ENTERED A RIGHT HAND CURVE. VHICLE ONE'S MOMENTUM CAUSED IT TO OVERTURN ONTO ITS DRIVER SIDE. FIRE DEPARTEMNT ASLO LIGHTENED DOME LID TO STOP THE LEAK IN THAT AREA. USES ENVRIONMENTAL COMPANY WAS DISPOACTED TO THE SCENCE TO HANGEL THE LOAD TRANSFER AND THE REMEDIATION AND CLEAN UP OF THE SITE. USES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1800. THE LOAD WAS SUCCESSFULLY TRANFERED FOR THE DAMAGED TRAILER TO ANOTHER CLEAN TANKER AT APPROXIMATELY 2100. USES CONTINUED WITH CLEAN UP OF SITE THROUGH THE EVENING AND COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 THE NEXT MORNING

column168: FUEL (#2 DIESEL) WAS BEING PUMPED FROM A SMALL TANKER TRUCK TO 2000 GAL AST AT CONVENIENCE STORE. AUTO SHUTOFF ON NOZZLE AT END OF FUELING HOSE FAILED AND DID NOT SHUT OFF WHEN AST WAS FULL. STORE OWNER CALCULATED 9 GAL OF DIESEL SPRAYED/LEAKED ONTO GROUND (ASPHALT PARKING LOT). SOME FUEL MIGRATED ACROSS PARKING LOT INTO STORM DRAIN INLET. NO FUEL EXITED STORM DRAIN TO ANY SURFACE WATER. OIL DRY WAS USED TO RECOVER A SMALL STORM OF FUEL ON PARKING LOT SURFACE. A VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO SUCK FUEL AMD 750 GAL OF WATER USED TO FLUSH OUT STORM DRAIN. ALL OIL DRY AND WATER/FUEL WAS PROPERTY DISPOSED OF. ACTUAL RELEASE DURATION WAS LIKELY LESS THAN 5 MINUTES.
column169: THE RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION WENT WELL. ALL DRIVERS CONDUCTING THIS TYPE OF FUELING FOR GREENEVILLE OIL HAVE UNDERWENT TRAINING TO APPLY OIL DRY AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS.

column168: DRIVER WAS DRIVING WEST ON MT. HIGHWAY 10 WEST OF 9 MILE EXIT AND EAST OF ALBERTON. COMING INTO A BLIND RIGHT HAND CURVE AS THE TREES CLEARED HE NOTICED A MOTORCYCLE APPROACHING HIM IN HIS WESTBOUND LANE. TO AVOID THE MOTORCYCLE WHO HAD NO CHANCE OF MAKING IT BACK INTO THE EASTBOUND LANE THE DRIVER STEERED LEFT AND LEFT HIS LANE TO AVOID THE MOTORCYCLE. THE TRACTOR STAYED UPRIGHT BUT THE TRAILER WAS SWERVING AND CAUGHT THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT WHICH TORE THE TRAILER OUT OF THE PINTLE HITCH CAUSING IT TO ROLL OVER INTO A RAVINE BASICALLY ON ITS TOP. THE CENTER SEAM//WELD AND PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF ONTO THE GROUND.
column169: I AM NOT SURE WHAT ALL I COULD RECOMMEND TO THE DRIVER TO BE MORE RESPONSIVE TO THIS SITUATION. IT WAS PURELY A JUDGEMENT CALL ON THE DRIVER'S PART AND I AM NOT SURE I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT HE DO ANYTHING DIFFERENT, AS HE CHOSE TO SAFE THE MOTORCYCLISTS LIFE.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FUEL INTO A UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. DRIVER MOVED TRUCK FORWARD WHILE STILL UNLOADING AND CAUGHT THE UNLOADING HOSE AND BROKE FITTING ON THE #3 LOADING HEAD. AS SOON AS IT HAPPENED, THE DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND SHUT THE INTERNAL TANK VALVE BY USING THE EMERGENCY SHUT DOWN CONTROL ON THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO PUT SPILL PADS AND ABSORBENT DOWN ON CONCRETE TO ABSORB THE FUEL.   ENVIRONMENTAL WORKS OF SPRINGFIELD MO WAS CONTACTED TO GO OUT AND CLEAN UP SPILL PADS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND MAKE SURE SITE WAS CLEAN.   TANK WAS TAKEN TO TRUX TRAILER REPAIR IN SPRINGFIELD MO. PIPING WAS REMOVED REPAIRED AND LEAK TESTED.
column169: DRIVER HAS BEEN RETRAINED ON PROCEDURES AND INSTRUCTED NOT TO MOVE THE TRUCK WHILE UNLOADING LINES ARE ATTACHED.

column168: I BACKED THE TRUCK INTO THE SPOT WE USED FOR FUELING. I GOT OUT THE OTHER GUYS WERE PUTTING THE CONES AND CHOCKS OUT. I STARTED PULLING THE HOSE AND GREGG TURNED THE PUMP ON. I GAVE THE NOZZLE TO THE SANGEL EMPLOYEE THAT FILLS THE OUTSIDE TANKS CLOSED TO THE WELLS. HE FINISHED AND GAVE ME BACK THE NOZZLE. I WENT BETWEEN THE LAST TWO HOSES DOWN TO FILL THEM. I TURNED ON THE NOZZLE AND IT STARTED FILLING AS NORMAL. BUT A FEW SECONDS LATER IT QUIT. I WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK TO FIND OUT WHY AND THAT’S WHEN I DISCOVERED THE FULL LEAK. I COULD SEE IT COMING FROM BEHIND A VALVE AND GASKET FAILED. WE THEN STARTED CLEANING THE SPILL
column169: CHECK GASKETS MORE OFTEN AND BE MORE AWARE OF SITUATIONS IMMEDIATELY.

column168: 5 PALLETS OF PRODUCT WERE LOADED ONTO A UNIT WITH NO DUNNAGE TO HOLD THE MATERIAL DURING TRANSIT. WHILE EN ROUTE TO DESTINATION, THE MATERIAL SHIFTED TO ONE SIDE CAUSING IT TO LOAD AND PINCH 2 BOXES ON BOTTOM LATER.      WHEN THE ASSOCIATED MOVED THE MATERIAL, THE BOXES SHIFTED AGAIN CAUSING A LEAK OF THE INNER CONTAINERS. A TOTAL OF 3 JUGS WERE PUNCTURED. LOSS OF MATERIAL APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON FROM ALL CONTAINERS.     SHIPMENT WAS RE-STACKED ONTO ANOTHER PALLET AND SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.
column169: CONTACT ORIGIN FACILITY AND COMMUNICATE TO ASSOCIATES THE IMPORTANCE OF USING DUNAGE TO AVOID FURTHER INCIDENTS.

column168: DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED DUE TO OPERATOR ERROR. TRANSPORTATION OPERATOR OPENED THE WRONG VALVE DURING FUEL DELIVERY, WHICH DISCHARGED FUEL FORM THE TRANSPORTATION CARGO TANK ONTO THE GROUND SURFACE. AREAS OF IMPACT INVOLVED ASPHALT, SOIL AND THE AST CATCH BASIN. FUEL DID MIGRATE INTO THE FIXED FACILITY STORM DRAIN SYSTEM. IMMEDIATE ACTIONS TAKEN WERE TO BUILD A SMALL SOIL DIKE AROUND THE RELEASE AREA AND CLOSE THE VALVE SYSTEMS ON STORM DRAIN OFF SITE DISCHARGE VALVE. NO FUEL LEFT THE FACILITY.     A RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR WAS IMMEDIATELY HIRED TO CONTAIN AND REMEDIATE THE RELEASE. ALL PETROLEUM IMPACTED SOILS WERE REMOVED AND CONFIRMATION SAMPLES EXTRACTED TO DETERMINED IF CLEANUP STANDARDS WERE OBTAINED. ALL SAMPLES RETURNED BELOW SALT LAKE COUNTRY HEALTH DEPARTMENT/ STATE OF UTAH DERR LEVELS. AREA WAS BACKED FILLED WITH CLEAN IMPORTED SOILS. ALL STORMS DRAIN LINES AND CATCH BASIN WERE JET ROD AND HYDRO VAC CLEANED. ALL WASTE GENERATED WAS TRANSPORTED OFF SITE AND DISPOSED OF AT PERMITTED FACILITIES.
column169: EMPLOYEES WERE RETAINED ON THE CARGO TANK VALVE SYSTEMS; ALL UNUSED CARGO TANK VALVES WILL BE CAPPED PRIOR TO UNLOADING OF FUEL.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS HAVING TROUBLE WITH THE #3 INTERNAL ON THE CTMV TRAILER, WHICH CLOSED ON HIM DURING THE DELIVERY. THE DRIVER BROKE THE CONNECTION AT THE DROP FITTING TO ALLOW SOME AIR INTO THE LINE AND WALKED OUT THE HOSE.THE DRIVER THEN DECIDED TO START THE TRUCK TO BUILD AIR PRESSURE. UNFORTUNATELY, THE DRIVER DID NOT CLOSE THE QUARTER TURNS AND HIS CONNECTIONS WERE NOT TIGHT. AS SOON AS THE TRUCK BUILT ENOUGH AIR PRESSURE THE INTERNAL OPENED. THE FORCE OF THE FUEL BLEW THE FITTING OFF THE TANK CONNECTION CAUSING A 5-10 GALLON SPILL OF DIESEL FUEL.     THE DRIVER AND THE FACILITY OPERATOR USED THEIR SPILL KITS TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THE RELEASE. AND THEY SUCCESSFULLY CLEANED UP THE RELEASE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED BUT THERE WERE NO INJURIES, DAMAGES, OR EVACUATIONS. THE DRIVER'S MANAGERS ALSO RESPONDED AND WAS ON SITE DURING THE CLEANUP.
column169: MANAGERS REVIEWED AND REINFORCED IMPORTANCE OF SAFE UNLOADING PROCEDURES WITH ALL DRIVERS. SPECIFIC OPERATING PROCEDURES (I.E., CLOSING QUARTER TURNS BEFORE STARTING TRUCK AND DOUBLE CHECKING CONNECTIONS) WERE REVIEWED.

column168: DRIVER SET OUT CONES BY DROPS AND TOOK ALL OTHER NECESSARY SAFETY PRECAUTIONS IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING. DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSES AND FITTINGS TO THE DROPS IN GROUND AND BEGAN TO UNLOAD. WHILE UNLOADING A WHITE CHEVROLET IMPALA DROVE OVER DROP FITTING IN GROUND AND CONTINUED DRIVING TO FLEE THE SCENE. THIS CAUSED THE DROP FITTING AND VAPOR FITTING TO CRACK, ALLOWING FOR A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALS. GASOLINE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY BEGAN USING SPILL PADS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND CALLED AUTHORITIES. LAFAYETTE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND BEGAN SPREADING OIL DRY ON THE AFFECTED AREA.
column169: IN THIS PARTICULAR INSTANCE I WOULD RECOMMEND NOTHING THAT THE DRIVER SHOULD’VE OR COULD'VE DONE DIFFERENTLY TO PREVENT THE SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT OUR DRIVER FOLLOWED ALL NECESSARY SAFETY PRECAUTIONS IN ORDER TO PREVENT THE SPILL, HOWEVER, THE ACCIDENT AND RESULTING SPILL WERE UNAVOIDABLE ON HIS PART. THE SPILL OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF HUMAN ERROR OF THE PARTY DRIVING THE CHEVROLET IMPALA.

column168: KEVIN COBB WAS PUMPING ON ROAD DIESEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND FUEL TANK (20,000 GALLON CAPACITY 12,000 AND 8,000 SPLIT TANK). WHILE TRANSFERRING FUEL INTO THE TANK, KEVIN WAS UNDER THE ASSUMPTION THAT THE TWO TANKS WERE MANIFOLDED TOGETHER. THIS WAS NOT THE CASE, HE OVERFILLED THE TANK PAST 90 PERCENT CAUSING OVERFILL OF THE TANK. THE OVERFILL VALVE ON THE ABOVE GROUND TANK BROKE WHICH STOPPED THE PRESSURE RELEASE FROM THE TANK AND BLEW THE VALVE OFF THE TANK. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER AS BEST AS HE COULD BEFORE FLETCHER OIL DISPATCHED KAM ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP TO THE SCENE.
column169: KEVIN HAS SINCE BEEN BROUGHT BACK TO TRAINING TO HELP HIM BETTER UNDERSTAND HOW TANK LOADING PROCEDURES AND TANK MONITORING SYSTEMS WORK.

column168: TRUCK WAS AT A STANDSTILL WAITING ON A RED LIGHT WAITING TO MAKE A LEFT TURN WITH SEVERAL OTHER VEHICLES. ONE WAS IN THE FRONT, ONE WAS FROM BEHIND AND ONE WAS TO THE SIDE. THE LIGHT TURNED GREEN AND EVERYONE PROCEEDED TO MAKE LEFT TURN. THE TRUCK HIT A DIP IN THE ROADWAY FROM WEAR AND TEAR AND THE FUEL SHIFTED AND ROLLED THE TRUCK. THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO ANYONE OR ANY OTHER VEHICLES.
column169: THIS WAS A FREAK ACCIDENT. DRIVER WAS ONLY DOING 10 MPH FROM A STANDSTILL. THE TRUCK HAD 3/4 OF THE FUEL OIL SHIFT WHEN THE CAR REACHED THE DIP IN THE ROAD WAY WHICH WAS ALSO SLANTED TOWARD THE GUTTERS CAUSING THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN AT A VERY SLOW RAT OF SPEED.

column168: INTRODUCTION    ON MAY 6, 2016, A TRACTOR AND TRAILER OPERATED BY ENGLAND EQUIPMENT COMPANY (ENGLUND) OF CASHION, ARIZONA, WAS PARKING FOR DRIVER DOWN TIME AT SENNETT TRAILER IN RIALTO, CALIFORNIA. WHEN THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE PARKED, THE DRIVER OBSERVED SOLID MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. LMH ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. WAS AUTHORIZED BY GREAT WEST CASUALTY COMPANY, THE INSURER FOR ENGLUND, TO DIRECT THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE.     BACKGROUND     SITE LOCATION AND DESCRIPTION    THE SPILL SITE IS LOCATED ON THE STREET IN FRONT OF 2824 NORTH LOCUST AVENUE, RIALTO, CALIFORNIA. THE FACILITY AT THIS LOCATION IS A TRAILER STORAGE YARD. THE SITE LOCATION IS INDICATED ON THE EXCERPT OF A USGS MAP ON FIGURE 1. AN AERIAL VIEW OF THIS LOCATION DOWNLOADED FROM GOOGLE EARTH IS PROVIDED IN FIGURE 2. A STREET VIEW OF THIS LOCATION DOWNLOADED FROM GOOGLE EARTH IS PROVIDED ON FIGURE 3.     DESCRIPTION OF SPILLED MATERIAL    THE MATERIAL SPILLED AT THE SITE WAS A SPENT CATALYST SHIPPED BY TESORO CORPORATION FORM ITS TESORO GOLDEN EAGLE REFINERY IN MARTINEZ, CALIFORNIA, FOR DISPOSAL. THE USDOT DESCRIPTION ON THE ORIGINAL MANIFEST IS UN3190, HAZARDOUS WASTE SELF-HEATING SOLID INORGANIC, NOS (NOT OTHERWISE SPECIFIED), (SPENT CATALYST), 4.2, PG II. THE MATERIAL WAS FURTHER DESCRIBED ON THE MANIFEST UNDER ADDITIONAL INFORMATION AS ‘SPENT NIMO CATALYST.” THIS MATERIAL IS USED IN PETROLEUM REFINERIES TO REMOVE SULFUR FROM REFINED PRODUCTS SUCH AS GASOLINE, JET FUEL, KEROSENE, DIESEL FUEL, AND FUEL OILS. THE PURPOSE OF REMOVING THE SULFUR IS TO REDUCE THE SULFUR DIOXIDE (SO2) EMISSIONS THAT RESULT FROM USING THOSE FUELS IN AUTOMOTIVE OR OTHER VEHICLES, AND IN RESIDENTIAL AND INDUSTRIAL FURNACES. A NIMO CATALYST IS TYPICALLY AN ALUMINA BASE IMPREGNATED WITH A COMBINATION OF NICKEL AND MOLYBDENUM (CALLED NICKEL-MOLY OR NIMO) USED FOR SPECIFIC DIFFICULT-TO-TREAT FEED STOCKS, SUCH AS THOSE CONTAINING A HIGH LEVEL OF CHEMICALLY-BOUND NITROGEN.     CATALYSTS SUCH AS THIS WILL IGNITE SPONTANEOUSLY IN AIR AT OR BELOW 55 C (130F) AND ARE REFERRED TO AS PYROPHORIC MATERIAL. PYROPHORIC MATERIALS ARE OFTEN WATER-REACTIVE AND WILL IGNITE WHEN THEY CONTACT WATER OR HUMID AIR. THEY CAN BE HANDLED SAFELY IN ATMOSPHERE OF ARGON OR (WITH A FEW EXCEPTIONS) NITROGEN. MOST PYROPHORIC FIRES SHOULD BE EXTINGUISHED WITH A CLASS D FIRE EXTINGUISHER FOR BURNING METALS.     THE CARGO WAS BEING SHIPPED TO GULF CHEMICAL AND METAL IN FREEPORT, TEXAS, FOR RECYCLING. A COPY OF THE ORIGINAL MANIFEST IS INCLUDED IN APPENDIX A. GULF CHEMICAL AND METAL TREATS NICKEL-MOLY CATALYST AND PRODUCES TECHNICAL –GRADE AND CHEMICAL-GRADE NICKEL-COBALT ALLOYS THAT ARE REUSED IN CHEMICAL AND METALLURGICAL APPLICATIONS BY CATALYST PRODUCERS AND STEEL MANUFACTURERS.     EMERGENCY RESPONSE    THE TRANSPORTER CONSISTED OF A TRUCK AND ONE TRAILER. THE MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER BY THE DRIVER WHEN HE WAS LEAVING THE SITE AFTER BEING PARKED FOR DOWNTIME. APPARENTLY
column169: ENGLUND EQUIPMENT COMPANY WILL NO LONGER TRANSPORT COUGAR BAGS OF ANY KIND.    BASED ON DISCUSSIONS WITH PERSONNEL ON SITE, DOCUMENTATION OF CLEANUP ACTIVITIES PROVIDED BY SBCHMD  AND DOUBLE BARREL, AND MANIFESTS FOR DISPOSAL OF WASTES AND FOR SHIPPING OF RECOVERED CARGO, LMH HAS CONCLUDED THAT THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT TO THE SITE OR SURROUNDINGS.     LMH RECOMMENDS NO ADDITIONAL ACTIVITIES.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS DRIVING NORTHBOUND ON HWY 85 APPROXIMATELY 0430 WHEN A SECOND SEMI PULLING A FLATBED DROP DECK TRAILER, ROLLED THROUGH A STOP SIGN AND THEN STOPPED WITH HIS TRAILER OBSTRUCTING THE NORTHBOUND LANES AND SHOULDER. GIVEN NIGHT TIME VISIBILITY, OUR TRUCK COULD NOT SEE THIS TRAILER UNTIL IT WAS TOO LATE. AT THIS TIME OUR TRUCK TRIED TO STOP LEAVING SKID MARKS SEVERAL HUNDRED FEET LONG. UPON IMPACT WITH THE STOPPED SEMI, THE TANK SHIFTED FORWARD LEAVING THE SUMPS OPEN. ALL CARGO WAS LOST.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE. OUR EQUIPMENT PERFORMED AS DESIGNED. THESE CARGO TANKS CANNOT TAKE FRONTAL IMPACT OF THIS MAGNITUDE. MAYBE A BETTER DESIGNED SHEAR COUPLING ON THE SUMP WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SUMP FROM TEARING OPEN.

column168: MICHAEL MORELAND CUSTOMER OF WEST CENTRAL AGISERVICES WAS PULLING TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WHEN THE ROUGH ROAD CAUSED THE TANK TO BOUNCE AND BREAK THE TONGUE THAT CONNECTED THE TANKS TO THE TRUCK. THE TANKS THEN CRASHED INTO THE DITCH. UPON IMPACT, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS DAMAGED CAUSING A RELEASE OF AN ESTIMATED 700-800 GALLONS. THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AROUND 11:15AM AND THE SCENE WAS COMPLETED CLEANED UP AND CLEARED BY 5PM.     DIRT WAS BROUGHT INTO STOP ANY SPILLAGE DOWN A DITCH AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, HOWEVER, MOST OF THE PRODUCT DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.     ATTACHED WITH THIS REPORT IS THE POLICE REPORT, AND A WRITTEN STATEMENT REPORT FORM THE LOCATION MANAGER AND SAFETY COORDINATOR FOR WCA HARRISONVILLE.

column168: The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
